      <title>Quantum weirdness</title>
      <link>https://tobydriscoll.net/blog/quantum-weirdness/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 24 Jul 2015 01:06:45 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://tobydriscoll.net/blog/quantum-weirdness/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;m a little late getting this news, but I&amp;rsquo;m fascinated by 
&lt;a href=&#34;http://physicsworld.com/cws/article/news/2015/may/26/do-atoms-going-through-a-double-slit-know-if-they-are-being-observed&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;an experiment at Australian National University&lt;/a&gt; showing (once again) in a vivid way 
&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.physics.org/toplistdetail.asp?id=17&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;how strange the quantum mechanical world is&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The experiment was a variation on the celebrated 
&lt;a href=&#34;https://www.google.com/url?sa=t&amp;amp;rct=j&amp;amp;q=&amp;amp;esrc=s&amp;amp;source=web&amp;amp;cd=10&amp;amp;cad=rja&amp;amp;uact=8&amp;amp;ved=0CEsQtwIwCWoVChMIwtfB6cbyxgIVipQNCh14iwhY&amp;amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fvideo.mit.edu%2Fwatch%2Fthomas-youngs-double-slit-experiment-8432%2F&amp;amp;ei=cIyxVcLfIYqpNviWosAF&amp;amp;usg=AFQjCNEnwjM9Ezlw12Hu4Ptbd88sJgWseg&amp;amp;sig2=5Yq58W4UySke647DGWG08Q&amp;amp;bvm=bv.98476267,d.eXY&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;double slit experiment&lt;/a&gt; that shows how photons are both particles &lt;em&gt;and&lt;/em&gt; waves, at least in some interpretations of the universe. That&amp;rsquo;s freakish in a not-news kind of way, as is the fact that the same is true of good old atoms, which might seem more as though they should stay particular all the time.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;One amusing view of the ANU experiment is that an atom can &amp;ldquo;decide&amp;rdquo; to be either particle-like or wave-like &lt;em&gt;based on information from the future.&lt;/em&gt; Just like 
&lt;a href=&#34;http://hitchhikers.wikia.com/wiki/Milliways&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;the restaurant at the end of the universe&lt;/a&gt;, that is, of course, impossible.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If I were a better physicist I could explain this to you, but in all honesty it was just the lack of intuitiveness about high energy physics (and maybe the contemporaneous demise of the 
&lt;a href=&#34;https://www.google.com/url?sa=t&amp;amp;rct=j&amp;amp;q=&amp;amp;esrc=s&amp;amp;source=web&amp;amp;cd=2&amp;amp;cad=rja&amp;amp;uact=8&amp;amp;ved=0CCgQFjABahUKEwi22sOdyfLGAhVM04AKHa4-CHQ&amp;amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.scientificamerican.com%2Farticle%2Fthe-supercollider-that-never-was%2F&amp;amp;ei=9o6xVbaHH8ymgwSu_aCgBw&amp;amp;usg=AFQjCNF6MtpZrD2FsH7s0Y8Hlp-t-QbspQ&amp;amp;sig2=NfTuJoyEzlpEgDq5RPY74g&amp;amp;bvm=bv.98476267,d.eXY&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;Superconducting Super Collider&lt;/a&gt;) that turned me off to the subject as an undergraduate. Still, what a universe to live in, eh Horatio?&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
